  "opinion": "As a mechanic who's been working in this field for over two decades, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine people's potential in STEM. Growing up in a family where my father had only completed lower secondary education but my mother finished upper secondary, I learned early that labels matter—especially when they're tied to gender or ethnicity. In Washington DC, where I've lived since I was 15 as an immigrant, I've noticed how students from marginalized backgrounds often hesitate to engage with science and math because they fear being labeled as 'not good at it.' For me, as a transgender person who's navigated a system that's often unwelcoming, this is especially true. I remember when I first started working on cars, I was told by a shop owner, 'You're not cut out for this,' but I didn't let that stop me. Stereotype threat isn't just about fear—it's about the internalized belief that you don't belong. It's why so many talented people don't pursue STEM fields because they're afraid of being judged. We need to address this by creating environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. In my shop, I've tried to model this by encouraging students to ask questions without shame, and it's made a real difference. The solution isn't about changing the curriculum but about changing the culture—making sure everyone knows they belong here, regardless of their background. As someone who's struggled with anxiety, I know that when people feel seen and supported, they can thrive.",
